115
00:09:41,331 --> 00:09:44,300
I wanted to play him.

116
00:09:44,367 --> 00:09:47,404
I wanted to create a sound.

117
00:09:49,972 --> 00:09:51,508
My sound.

118
00:09:53,477 --> 00:09:57,014
This... is my design.

119
00:10:28,458 --> 00:10:30,860
I worry that I've made
Franklyn feel powerless.

120
00:10:32,931 --> 00:10:36,055
He wants to be my friend.

121
00:10:36,175 --> 00:10:39,852
His obsession with me is
interfering with his progress.

122
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:42,975
I'm considering referring
him to another doctor.

123
00:10:43,095 --> 00:10:45,909
Referrals can be complicated.

124
00:10:46,980 --> 00:10:49,382
I referred you
to another psychiatrist.

125
00:10:49,450 --> 00:10:51,417
You refused.

126
00:10:51,486 --> 00:10:53,687
I'm more tenacious
than Franklyn.

127
00:10:53,754 --> 00:10:57,125
Why were you so tenacious?

128
00:10:58,236 --> 00:11:01,676
I feel protective of you.
You support me

129
00:11:01,796 --> 00:11:05,867
as a colleague and psychiatrist,
and as a human being.

130
00:11:05,935 --> 00:11:09,405
I want to be supportive
of you... after what happened.

131
00:11:09,473 --> 00:11:15,011
I'm not the only psychiatrist who's
ever been attacked by a patient.

132
00:11:15,079 --> 00:11:16,843
I hesitated to even bring up
the subject

133
00:11:16,963 --> 00:11:20,585
of an obsessive patient because
of your traumatic experience.

134
00:11:20,652 --> 00:11:24,656
Hannibal...

135
00:11:24,724 --> 00:11:28,193
I'm your psychiatrist;
you're not mine.

136
00:11:35,269 --> 00:11:37,103
Played him
like a fiddle.

137
00:11:37,171 --> 00:11:38,672
Along with rosin powder,

138
00:11:38,740 --> 00:11:41,699
we found sodium carbonate,
sulfur dioxide, lye,

139
00:11:41,819 --> 00:11:42,958
and olive oil in the wounds.

140
00:11:43,078 --> 00:11:44,832
What is the deal with
the olive oil?

141
00:11:44,952 --> 00:11:47,181
- Sure wasn't making salad.
- He removed anything

142
00:11:47,301 --> 00:11:50,431
non-muscular or fatty
from around the vocal folds.

143
00:11:50,551 --> 00:11:54,056
The chords themselves were treated
with a sulfur dioxide solution.

144
00:11:54,124 --> 00:11:57,927
The sulfur dioxide had the effect
of hardening the vocal chords.

145
00:11:57,995 --> 00:12:00,263
Made them easier to play.

146
00:12:00,330 --> 00:12:05,569
Had to open you up to get
a decent sound out of you.

147
00:12:09,574 --> 00:12:13,078
You pick it up and can't play
it, he'll put you down and play you.

148
00:12:13,146 --> 00:12:16,716
He took the time to whiten
the vocal chords before playing them.

149
00:12:16,784 --> 00:12:20,386
It's not about whitening them; It was
about, um, increasing elasticity.

150
00:12:20,453 --> 00:12:24,157
He treated the vocal chords the
same way you treat catgut string.

151
00:12:24,224 --> 00:12:27,327
Yes, I played the violin.

152
00:12:31,533 --> 00:12:33,968
This takes a steady hand.

153
00:12:34,036 --> 00:12:36,038
A confidence.

154
00:12:36,106 --> 00:12:38,240
He's killed before.

155
00:12:38,308 --> 00:12:41,744
- Like this?
- No, not like this.

156
00:12:41,812 --> 00:12:44,415
This is a skilled musician

157
00:12:44,482 --> 00:12:46,917
trying a new instrument.

158
00:12:56,495 --> 00:12:59,398
Among the first musical
instruments were flutes

159
00:12:59,466 --> 00:13:01,500
carved from human bone.

160
00:13:03,471 --> 00:13:04,904
This murder was

161
00:13:04,972 --> 00:13:07,908
a performance.

162
00:13:07,976 --> 00:13:10,478
Every life is a piece of music.

163
00:13:10,546 --> 00:13:14,149
Like music, we are finite
events, unique arrangements,

164
00:13:14,217 --> 00:13:17,052
sometimes harmonious,
sometimes dissonant.

165
00:13:17,120 --> 00:13:20,022
Sometimes
not worth hearing again.

166
00:13:20,090 --> 00:13:23,326
- He's a poet and a psychopath.
- And a craftsman.

167
00:13:23,394 --> 00:13:26,063
He was shrinking and tanning
the vocal chords.

168
00:13:26,131 --> 00:13:29,900
Like turning iron wire
into musical steel string.

169
00:13:29,968 --> 00:13:32,237
Was there olive oil?

170
00:13:34,206 --> 00:13:36,308
- Yes.
- Whatever sound

171
00:13:36,376 --> 00:13:38,944
he was trying to produce,
it was an authentic one.

172
00:13:39,012 --> 00:13:43,383
Olive oil hasn't been used in the
production of catgut for over a century.

173
00:13:43,450 --> 00:13:46,586
It was said to increase
the life of the strings

174
00:13:46,654 --> 00:13:49,756
and create a sweeter,
more melodic sound.

175
00:13:49,824 --> 00:13:52,126
No, I hear what
he was playing

176
00:13:52,194 --> 00:13:54,095
behind my eyes
when I close them.

177
00:13:54,163 --> 00:13:57,933
What do you see
behind closed eyes?

178
00:14:02,538 --> 00:14:06,276
Um... I see myself.

179
00:14:06,343 --> 00:14:09,013
You said the killer was
performing.

180
00:14:09,080 --> 00:14:12,149
- Who was he performing for?
- I don't know. Um...

181
00:14:12,217 --> 00:14:15,520
Patron of the arts?
A fellow musician? Or...

182
00:14:15,587 --> 00:14:17,021
Another killer?

183
